This paper is about dialogue modeling using a conditional Wasserstein autoencoder (WAE). The main focus is on generating diverse and informative responses, which falls under the category of natural language processing (NLP) and specifically, conversational AI. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.CL (Computation and Language). The paper also involves training a GAN within the latent variable space, which is related to generative models and deep learning, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) another likely category. Additionally, the paper involves optimizing the Wasserstein distance, which is a common technique in optimization and numerical analysis, making cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) another possible category. The paper also involves developing a Gaussian mixture prior network, which is related to probabilistic modeling, making cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) another possible category. Finally, the paper involves using neural networks to transform context-dependent random noise, which is related to computer vision and image processing, making cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) another possible category.
